<h2 id="getting-started">Getting started</h2>
<p>Want to learn more about Jekyll? Check out <a
href="https://www.taniarascia.com/make-a-static-website-with-jekyll/">this
tutorial</a>. Why Jekyll? Read <a
href="https://karpathy.github.io/2014/07/01/switching-to-jekyll/">Andrej
Karpathy’s blog post</a>!</p>
<h2 id="installing">Installing</h2>
<p>For installation details please refer to <a
href="INSTALL.md">INSTALL.md</a>.</p>
<h2 id="customizing">Customizing</h2>
<p>For customization details please refer to <a
href="CUSTOMIZE.md">CUSTOMIZE.md</a>.</p>
<h2 id="features">Features</h2>
<h3 id="lightdark-mode">Light/Dark Mode</h3>
<p>This template has a built-in light/dark mode. It detects the user
preferred color scheme and automatically switches to it. You can also
manually switch between light and dark mode by clicking on the sun/moon
icon in the top right corner of the page.</p>
<p align="center">
<img src="readme_preview/light.png" width=400>
<img src="readme_preview/dark.png" width=400>
</p>
<hr />
<h3 id="cv">CV</h3>
<p>There are currently 2 different ways of generating the CV page
content. The first one is by using a json file located in <a
href="assets/json/resume.json">assets/json/resume.json</a>. It is a <a
href="https://jsonresume.org/">known standard</a> for creating a CV
programmatically. The second one, currently used as a fallback when the
json file is not found, is by using a yml file located in <a
href="_data/cv.yml">_data/cv.yml</a>. This was the original way of
creating the CV page content and since it is more human readable than a
json file we decided to keep it as an option.</p>
<p>What this means is, if there is no resume data defined in <a
href="_config.yml">_config.yml</a> and loaded via a json file, it will
load the contents of <a href="_data/cv.yml">_data/cv.yml</a> as
fallback.</p>
<p><a href="https://alshedivat.github.io/al-folio/cv/"><img
src="readme_preview/cv.png" alt="CV Preview" /></a></p>
<hr />
<h3 id="people">People</h3>
<p>You can create a people page if you want to feature more than one
person. Each person can have its own short bio, profile picture, and you
can also set if every person will appear at the same or opposite
sides.</p>
<p><a href="https://alshedivat.github.io/al-folio/people/"><img
src="readme_preview/people.png" alt="People Preview" /></a></p>
<hr />
<h3 id="publications">Publications</h3>
<p>Your publications’ page is generated automatically from your BibTex
bibliography. Simply edit <a
href="_bibliography/papers.bib">_bibliography/papers.bib</a>. You can
also add new <code>*.bib</code> files and customize the look of your
publications however you like by editing <a
href="_pages/publications.md">_pages/publications.md</a>. By default,
the publications will be sorted by year and the most recent will be
displayed first. You can change this behavior and more in the
<code>Jekyll Scholar</code> section in <a
href="_config.yml">_config.yml</a> file.</p>
<p>You can add extra information to a publication, like a PDF file in
the <a href="assets/pdf/">assets/pdf/</a> directory and add the path to
the PDF file in the BibTeX entry with the <code>pdf</code> field. Some
of the supported fields are: <code>abstract</code>,
<code>altmetric</code>, <code>arxiv</code>, <code>bibtex_show</code>,
<code>blog</code>, <code>code</code>, <code>dimensions</code>,
<code>doi</code>, <code>eprint</code>, <code>html</code>,
<code>isbn</code>, <code>pdf</code>, <code>pmid</code>,
<code>poster</code>, <code>slides</code>, <code>supp</code>,
<code>video</code>, and <code>website</code>.</p>
<p><a href="https://alshedivat.github.io/al-folio/publications/"><img
src="readme_preview/publications.png"
alt="Publications Preview" /></a></p>
<hr />
<h3 id="collections">Collections</h3>
<p>This Jekyll theme implements <code>collections</code> to let you
break up your work into categories. The theme comes with two default
collections: <code>news</code> and <code>projects</code>. Items from the
<code>news</code> collection are automatically displayed on the home
page. Items from the <code>projects</code> collection are displayed on a
responsive grid on projects page.</p>
<p><a href="https://alshedivat.github.io/al-folio/projects/"><img
src="readme_preview/projects.png" alt="Projects Preview" /></a></p>
<p>You can easily create your own collections, apps, short stories,
courses, or whatever your creative work is. To do this, edit the
collections in the <a href="_config.yml">_config.yml</a> file, create a
corresponding folder, and create a landing page for your collection,
similar to <code>_pages/projects.md</code>.</p>
<hr />
<h3 id="layouts">Layouts</h3>
<p><strong>al-folio</strong> comes with stylish layouts for pages and
blog posts.</p>
<h4 id="the-iconic-style-of-distill">The iconic style of Distill</h4>
<p>The theme allows you to create blog posts in the <a
href="https://distill.pub/">distill.pub</a> style:</p>
<p><a
href="https://alshedivat.github.io/al-folio/blog/2021/distill/"><img
src="readme_preview/distill.png" alt="Distill Preview" /></a></p>
<p>For more details on how to create distill-styled posts using
<code>&lt;d-*&gt;</code> tags, please refer to <a
href="https://alshedivat.github.io/al-folio/blog/2021/distill/">the
example</a>.</p>
<h4 id="full-support-for-math-code">Full support for math &amp;
code</h4>
<p><strong>al-folio</strong> supports fast math typesetting through <a
href="https://www.mathjax.org/">MathJax</a> and code syntax highlighting
using <a href="https://github.com/jwarby/jekyll-pygments-themes">GitHub
style</a>. Also supports <a href="https://www.chartjs.org/">chartjs
charts</a>, <a href="https://mermaid-js.github.io/mermaid/#/">mermaid
diagrams</a>, and <a href="https://tikzjax.com/">TikZ figures</a>.</p>
<p align="center">
<a href="https://alshedivat.github.io/al-folio/blog/2015/math/" target="_blank"><img src="readme_preview/math.png" width=400></a>
<a href="https://alshedivat.github.io/al-folio/blog/2015/code/" target="_blank"><img src="readme_preview/code.png" width=400></a>
</p>
<h4 id="photos-audio-video-and-more">Photos, Audio, Video and more</h4>
<p>Photo formatting is made simple using <a
href="https://getbootstrap.com/docs/4.4/layout/grid/">Bootstrap’s grid
system</a>. Easily create beautiful grids within your blog posts and
project pages, also with support for <a
href="https://alshedivat.github.io/al-folio/blog/2023/videos/">video</a>
and <a
href="https://alshedivat.github.io/al-folio/blog/2023/audios/">audio</a>
embeds:</p>
<p align="center">
<a href="https://alshedivat.github.io/al-folio/projects/1_project/">
<img src="readme_preview/photos-screenshot.png" width="75%"> </a>
</p>
<hr />
<h3 id="other-features">Other features</h3>
<h4 id="githubs-repositories-and-user-stats">GitHub’s repositories and
user stats</h4>
<p><strong>al-folio</strong> uses <a
href="https://github.com/anuraghazra/github-readme-stats">github-readme-stats</a>
and <a
href="https://github.com/ryo-ma/github-profile-trophy">github-profile-trophy</a>
to display GitHub repositories and user stats on the
<code>/repositories/</code> page.</p>
<p><a href="https://alshedivat.github.io/al-folio/repositories/"><img
src="readme_preview/repositories.png"
alt="Repositories Preview" /></a></p>
<p>Edit the <code>_data/repositories.yml</code> and change the
<code>github_users</code> and <code>github_repos</code> lists to include
your own GitHub profile and repositories to the
<code>/repositories/</code> page.</p>
<p>You may also use the following codes for displaying this in any other
pages.</p>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb1"><pre
